## External integration docs (optional)

Cache vendor APIs/XSDs/PDFs/OpenAPI under `.work/docs/integration/` (per-project cache under project memory — always local in both fat- and thin-client modes). Rules: organize by source+version subfolders (no silent overwrite on upgrade); log every download in `.work/docs/integration/MANIFEST.txt`; prefer official domains; never store keys/PEM/tokens/`.env`; verify file type after download; vendor artifacts only. Read cached copies during implementation; refresh when versions change.

---

## Protected Files

- **File access override:** read any path the user provides, regardless of `.gitignore`.
- **Do NOT modify unless explicitly asked:** paths in `.work/PROTECTED_SURFACES.json` (deploy scripts, templates, CI). Consumer examples: `package.json`, `docker-compose*.yml`, `Dockerfile.*`, `frontend/`, `.env*`.
- **If a protected file needs a change:** stop, explain why, ask permission.

---

## Data Privacy & Security

- **Sensitive data:** keep production/customer data local without approval; use the repo sanitizer (e.g. `.obfuscation/sanitize_data.py`) before loading exports/XML; prefer sanitized copies over raw.
- **No PII in logs:** never log full objects with PII (emails, phones, gov IDs, amounts) — log internal IDs/status only; sanitize errors.
- **Debug scripts:** no embedded sensitive data; use `.env` or runtime values; ask before re-running when a var is missing.
- **Secret scrubbing:** before reading/emitting text, ensure no keys/tokens/passwords appear (`[REDACTED]`); never display credentials or raw `.env`.
- **Test data:** synthetic/mock only; never hardcode real emails/IDs; no unsanitized prod dumps in tests.
- **File hygiene:** delete temp files after use; write `.xls/.xlsx/.csv/.xml/.json` exports to `tmp/`, not the source tree.

---

## Database & Schema Rules

- **New tables:** register models in the bounded context's persistence module (no global grab-bag). Table creation = idempotent SQL under `backend/migrations/` via `@db-migration` (models are source of truth).
- **Schema ledger:** permanent append-only history of structural fixes; never prune; each entry idempotent (`ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS`).
- **Migration policy** (numbered SQL under `backend/migrations/`, procedure `@db-migration`):
  1. `backend/app/core/migration_runner.py` runs all scripts alphanumerically on every app start, before serving traffic; each must be idempotent.
  2. Verify idempotency (`@db-migration verify` or run runner twice on a dev DB) before claiming done.
  3. After stack start, confirm runner logs (`result: ok`) and spot-check schema/data.
  4. One-off/destructive/non-numbered/manual migrations require explicit human approval in-message — present exact SQL; the human runs it.
  5. Ad-hoc `INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE` on shared/dev DBs for tests needs explicit in-message approval; prefer fixtures/factories/mocks.
- **Backfills: STRICTLY PROHIBITED** by agents against shared DBs — describe the SQL for manual execution.

---

## Docker / Dev Environment

- When the project uses Compose, **never** run bare `npm/yarn/next/python/pytest/pip install` or type-checkers on the host — run all app test/lint/type/build commands inside the documented compose service. Installing service deps on the host bloats and dirties it; containers isolate the toolchain.

| Action | Where |
|--------|-------|
| Install deps for a service | Inside that service's compose container |
| Tests, lint, type-check, builds | `docker compose exec <service> …` |
| Rare host command | Only if `DOCS_TECH_STACK.md` documents it, or the user approves in-message |

```bash
# tests/lint/type (customize service + paths)
docker compose exec api bash -c "cd /app && pytest tests/ -q"
# one-off script (run from WORKDIR so imports resolve)
docker compose exec api bash -c "cd /app && timeout 120 python scripts/my_script.py"
```

Container identity via `.env` (`COMPOSE_PROJECT_NAME`, ports, `COMPOSE_PROJECT_NAME`); prefer `./dev-stack.sh` for isolated compose. Skills (`code-implementation`, `code-verify`) must use these commands, not hardcoded names from another project. Place one-off scripts under `backend/scripts/`. If the project does **not** use Docker, use the local/CI commands from `DOCS_TECH_STACK.md`.

---

## Workflow Rules

- **Planning:** plans live under `.work/plans/`. Wait for approval before large code changes when a plan-only was requested; confirm before editing when scope is unclear.
- **Deletion:** NEVER delete files without explicit user permission.
- **Task refs** (e.g. `PROJ-456`, `PROJ-T-23`) link commits to work items:
  1. User-provided ref (request/HANDOFF/branch) → prepend `REF: ` to every commit subject.
  2. No ref but work belongs to a task → ask once before committing; never guess/invent.
  3. No ref (exploratory/docs/chore) → conventional `type:` is fine.
- **Git:**
  - NEVER `git commit`/`push` unless the user requests it in the same message.
  - `@session-control close commit` / `commit` (and `push` variants): you MUST run shell `git add` + `git commit` per `.ai/skills/session-control/skill.md` (C4b / Commit protocol) — stage all safe dirty paths (default scope), then `git push` if requested. Show `git log -1 --oneline` + `git status -sb`; no "committed" claim without a SHA. `commit` variants skip HANDOFF/NEXT (session stays open).
  - `prepare-commit-msg` hook auto-prepends the ref when the branch contains one and strips `Co-authored-by:` trailers. Don't bypass hooks unless the user requests `--no-verify`.
  - Never modify history (rebase, force-push) without explicit request.
- **No attribution:** never add "Generated by", "Created by", dates, or agent signatures.
- **No `Co-authored-by:` (mandatory):** never add co-author trailers (Cursor/Copilot/any agent) or `--trailer`. Enforced by hooks (`prepare-commit-msg` strips, `commit-msg` rejects). Install once: `bash /mnt/work/Projects/.ai/scripts/install-git-hooks.sh` (auto via bootstrap/deploy).

---

## Verification & Communication

- **Before "complete":** run applicable tests + lint/type; confirm no regression; report actual output, not assumed.
- **On failure:** report exact error, diagnose root cause, fix, re-run.
- **Scope:** declare scope first (§ Change safety); `touch-scope-verify` + `blast-radius-check` enforce it.
- **Communication:** be concise; surface blockers early; label uncertainty; distinguish confirmed facts / inferences / proposals.

---

## OpenSpec (optional)

If used: proposals first for new/significant changes; implement exactly as approved; lifecycle commands under `.ai/commands/openspec/`. If unused, delete this section.

## External docs

Use Context7 MCP (`@upstash/context7-mcp`) for version-specific library docs when configured; else web-search to verify current APIs before writing integration code.

---

## Commit Message Format

- Plain text; no surrounding quotes or wrapping parentheses.
- Subject (≤72 chars, imperative): `REF-123: subject` when a ref is known (HANDOFF, GitHub task registry, branch, or last commit), else `type: description`.
- Optional body after a blank line (~72 col): explain **why**, not the file list.
- Types (no ref): `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `docs`, `chore`, `style`, `test`.
- **Readable by all audiences:** subject understandable by non-technical stakeholders; keep jargon/codenames in the body.
- When `github_task_registry_enabled`, the AI may query `GET /v1/projects/{id}/github/task-registry` for the ref (optional; fall back to HANDOFF/branch/last-commit). Ref prefixes are auto-linked inbound on GitHub sync via `commit_subject_refs` (idempotent) — always prefer `REF: subject` when a ref is known.
- Correct: `PROJ-456: Add login form with email validation` · `fix: handle empty payload on webhook retry`. Wrong: `"fix(webhook): empty payload"`.

---

## Documentation layout (`.ai/` vs `.work/`)

- **`.ai/`:** framework-only — skills, concepts, workflow guides, `START_HERE.md`, `PROCESS_ROUTER.md`, `templates/`, plus framework-wide contract/schema docs (e.g. `MASTER_PLAN_STANDARD.md`). **Never created by `@deploy-basic`** (thin-client). Fat-client only via `@deploy-files` / `@project-bootstrap init` when you explicitly vend a local copy. Pointer READMEs only under `.ai/plans/`, `.ai/features/`.
- **`.work/`:** **all project-specific memory and customization** — plans, SPECs, ADRs, prompts, `HANDOFF.md`, `PROTECTED_SURFACES.json`, binding **`.work/standards/`**, and **`.work/docs/`** (including vendor **`.work/docs/integration/`** cache). Generated filenames use the `YYYYMMDD-` prefix (except `NEXT.md`, `HANDOFF.md`). Always local in **both** fat- and thin-client modes — never resolved from `$AGENT_OS_SOURCE`.

| Path | Layer |
|------|-------|
| `.work/plans/` | Plans, registries, `NEXT.md` |
| `.work/features/` | Feature SPECs |
| `.work/decisions/` | ADRs |
| `.work/prompts/` | Questionnaires; user scratch |
| `.work/context/HANDOFF.md` | Session handoff |
| `.work/PROTECTED_SURFACES.json` | This project's high-blast paths |
| `.work/standards/` | This project's binding engineering standards (generated, not vendored) |
| `.work/docs/integration/` | This project's vendor/API integration cache |
| `.work/docs/` | Project docs (`guides/`, `tutorials/`, `reference/`, `features/`) |
| `.ai/skills/` | Portable agent skills (fat-client local, or `$AGENT_OS_SOURCE` in thin-client) |
| `.ai/standards/MASTER_PLAN_STANDARD.md` | Framework-wide master-plan structural contract (shared, not project-specific) |
| `.ai/templates/cursorrules.template` | Copy to repo-root `.cursorrules` when bootstrapping |

